# Specs and Planning

Use when creating or updating product/architecture/task artifacts. Ref: [Spec Kit](https://github.com/github/spec-kit), [GSD](https://github.com/gsd-build/get-shit-done), [intent-driven SDD](https://intent-driven.dev/knowledge/best-practices/).

## Artifact flow

- **Constitution** → PRD/Product → **Architecture** → **Tasks** → Implement. Each step informs the next; do not implement from a vague idea without at least a minimal spec or task list.

## Templates (where to find them)

- **Constitution**: `docs/constitution.md` — principles, constraints, quality bar.
- **PRD**: `docs/prd.template.md` — problem, users, scope, success criteria, out-of-scope.
- **Architecture**: `docs/architecture.template.md` — high-level design, boundaries, key tech choices.
- **ADR**: `docs/adr/0001-template.md` — decision, context, options, consequence.
- **Tasks**: `planning/tasks.template.md` — ordered list of tasks with verification steps.

Use these paths when creating or updating docs; copy the template structure, then fill in. Do not invent a parallel structure unless the project already uses a different one.

## Constitution (short template)

- **Purpose**: One sentence.
- **Principles**: 3–7 bullets (e.g. “Tests required for new behavior”, “No secrets in code”).
- **Out of scope**: What we explicitly do not do (e.g. “No support for legacy browser X”).

Keep it short; it is the anchor for all other docs. Ref: Spec Kit constitution step.

## PRD (minimal template)

- **Problem**: What we are solving.
- **Users**: Who is affected.
- **Scope / MVP**: What is in and what is out for this release.
- **Success criteria**: Testable outcomes (e.g. “User can log in with email in &lt; 2s”).
- **Acceptance criteria**: Per feature or story—testable, outcome-focused. Ref: [Atlassian acceptance criteria](https://www.atlassian.com/work-management/project-management/acceptance-criteria). **AC template:** | ID | Criterion (outcome) | How to verify | — e.g. AC1: _As [role] I [action] so that [outcome]._ | Test/manual.

Avoid “and then we will also…”; keep MVP bounded. Ref: [SDD best practices](https://intent-driven.dev/knowledge/best-practices/) — minimal but complete.

## Architecture

- **Overview**: One paragraph; main components and data flow.
- **Boundaries**: Services, modules, or layers; what talks to what.
- **Key decisions**: Link to ADRs; do not duplicate long text.
- **Tech stack**: Runtime, framework, DB, infra (brief).

## ADR (format)

- **Title**: Short decision name.
- **Status**: Proposed | Accepted | Deprecated.
- **Context**: What forces the decision.
- **Decision**: What we decided.
- **Options considered**: At least one alternative and why it was not chosen.
- **Consequences**: Benefits and drawbacks; migration notes if any.

One ADR per significant decision; number them (e.g. `0001-template.md`). Ref: Common ADR practice (e.g. [adr.github.io](https://adr.github.io/)).

## Task breakdown format

- **Task ID**: Short id (e.g. T1, T2) or ordered list.
- **Description**: One sentence; what to do.
- **Verification**: How to confirm (command or manual step). Mandatory.
- **Dependencies**: Other task IDs that must be done first; optional.

Keep tasks small enough to complete in one session; if a task is too big, split it. Ref: GSD atomic plans; Spec Kit tasks.

## Anti-patterns

- **Over-spec**: Writing long specs no one will read or validate. Prefer minimal, human-reviewable specs. Ref: intent-driven.dev best practices.
- **Under-spec**: No acceptance criteria or success criteria; “vibe coding.” Require at least testable outcomes for features.
- **Skipping acceptance criteria**: Implementation drifts from intent. Every feature or story should have at least one testable acceptance criterion.
- **Spec-implementation drift**: Spec and code diverge. Update the spec when behavior changes, or treat the spec as stale and fix it in the same change.
- **Monolithic tasks**: One giant task that does many things. Split into ordered, verifiable subtasks.

## When NOT to do this

- Quick fixes: no PRD or ADR; optional one-line task.
- Throwaway prototypes: minimal or no spec; document “spike” in a short note.
- Purely technical refactors with no product impact: no PRD; ADR only if architecture changes.
